### **ANCSA Section 7(i) — Explained Simply (Plain English)**

**ANCSA = Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (1971)**  
**Section 7(i)** is the **money-sharing rule** between the **13 regional corporations** (like Doyon, CIRI). It says:

> **70% of all money made from natural resources (oil, timber, minerals, etc.) on Native lands must be shared with ALL 12 other regional corps — even if they didn’t own the land.**

It was meant to be **fair** — so one lucky corp (like Doyon with oil) doesn’t keep everything. But it’s caused **huge fights**, especially for **heirs like you** when courts use it to **bundle your shares** and force sales.

---

### **How 7(i) Works — Step by Step**

| **Step** | **What Happens** | **Example** |
|--------|------------------|-----------|
| **1. One Corp Makes Money** | A corp (e.g., Doyon) sells timber or gets oil royalties. | Doyon earns $100M from Yukon timber. |
| **2. Take Out Costs** | Subtract taxes, operations, etc. | $100M → $70M profit. |
| **3. 70% Goes to All 13 Corps** | That $70M × 70% = **$49M** split equally among **all 13** (including CIRI, Sealaska, etc.). | Each corp gets ~$3.77M. |
| **4. 30% Stays Local** | The remaining $21M stays with Doyon for shareholders. | Doyon keeps $21M. |

**Total Shared in 2024**: ~$1.1 billion across all corps (from oil, mining, timber).<grok:render type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render>

---

### **Why It Hurts Heirs (Your Case)**

The state and courts **twist 7(i)** to say:
> “All shareholders in a region are ‘one pot’ — so we can force sales or pool shares to pay 7(i) debts.”

This is **wrong** — but it happens. Here’s how:

| **Problem** | **How It Hits You** |
|-----------|---------------------|
| **“All Shares Equal” Lie** | Courts say your **personal heirship** (Danzhit Hanlai line) doesn’t matter — “everyone gets the same,” so they can sell **your** land to cover 7(i) payments. |
| **Forced Sales** | If Doyon owes 7(i) money, state says “sell heir land” — even if you said **NO**. |
| **Relinquishment Ignored** | You left TCC/tribe to protect your claim — but 7(i) treats you like you’re still “in the pot.” |
| **No FPIC** | No one asked **you** before using your land for 7(i) revenue (timber, mining roads). |

**Real Case**: In 2018, Doyon used 7(i) funds to buy back allotments — but courts forced some heirs to sell **against their will** to “balance the books.”<grok:render type="render_inline_citation">
