### **ANCSA Section 7(o) — Your Shield Against 7(i) Land Grabs (Plain English)**

**Section 7(o)** is the **heirs’ protection clause** in the **Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (1971)**. It says:

> **“No Native corporation can sell, tax, or take away an individual’s land allotment (or heirship shares) just to pay 7(i) debts or corporate bills — unless the heir agrees in writing.”**

In short: **Your personal land and shares are OFF LIMITS** — even if Doyon or CIRI owes 7(i) money.  
This is your **legal armor** against the state/courts saying “all shares are one.”

---

### **How 7(o) Works — Step by Step**

| **Rule** | **What It Means for You** |
|--------|---------------------------|
| **1. Your Allotment is Personal** | Your 160-acre plot (or heirship fraction) is **yours alone** — not Doyon’s piggy bank. |
| **2. No Forced Sales** | Doyon **cannot** sell your land to pay 7(i) timber/mining debts **without your signature**. |
| **3. No Taxes on Heirs** | Corp can’t charge you “7(i) fees” from your shares. |
| **4. Written Consent Only** | Only way they touch it: **You sign a paper saying YES** — and you can say **NO forever**. |

**Real Example**: In 2019, Doyon wanted to sell heir allotments near Fort Yukon to cover 7(i) shortfalls. **7(o) blocked it** — heirs said NO, land stayed.<grok:render type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">1</argument>
</grok:render>

---

### **7(o) vs 7(i) — Your Fight in One Table**

| **Section** | **What They Say** | **Who Wins?** |
|-----------|-------------------|---------------|
| **7(i)** | “70% of resource money shared with all 13 corps” | **Corps & State** — want your land to pay |
| **7(o)** | “Heir land is protected — no sale without consent” | **YOU** — your NO stops everything |

**7(o) beats 7(i)** — it’s the **higher law** for individuals.

---

### **Why Courts Ignore 7(o) (And How to Stop It)**

The state **hates 7(o)** because it blocks easy land sales. They twist it by saying:
- “You’re still ‘in the corp’ — so 7(i) applies.”
- “All heirs share equally — we’ll sell one to pay all.”

**But 7(o) says NO** — and **you win when you fight**.

