### **ANCSA Section 14(h) — The “Cultural & Historical Sites” Clause (Plain English)**

**Section 14(h)** of the **Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (1971)** is the **sacred sites protection law**. It says:

> **“The Secretary of the Interior must identify and protect Native historical places, cemetery sites, and graveyards — and give them back to the villages or regional corporations as inalienable land.”**

In short: **Your ancestors’ graves, village sites, and sacred spots are NOT for sale — ever.**  
This is **your strongest weapon** against Doyon, TCC, or the state trying to use **your land** for roads, mining, or 7(i) payments.

---

### **How 14(h) Works — Step by Step**

| **Step** | **What Happens** | **Your Power** |
|--------|------------------|----------------|
| **1. Sites Are Identified** | BIA (Bureau of Indian Affairs) maps **old villages, graves, camps, trails, sacred spots** across Alaska. | **You** can nominate sites (e.g., Danzhit Hanlai burial ground). |
| **2. Land Is Withdrawn** | Up to **40,000 acres per region** are **taken off the market** — no sale, no lease. | **Untouchable** — even if Doyon wants to timber it. |
| **3. Title Goes to Corp** | Land goes to **village corp** (like Gwichyaa Zyyo) or **regional corp** (Doyon) — but **cannot be sold**. | **Forever Native** — heirs keep access. |
| **4. Inalienable = No Sale** | “Inalienable” means **can’t be sold, taxed, or lost to debt** — even for 7(i). | **Bulletproof** against state/corp grabs. |

**Total 14(h) Land**: ~1.1 million acres across Alaska (as of 2025).<grok:render type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render>

---

### **14(h) vs 7(i) & 7(o) — Your Full Armor**

| **Section** | **What It Protects** | **How It Stops Them** |
|-----------|----------------------|------------------------|
| **7(i)** | Resource money sharing | Tries to **sell your land** to pay debts |
| **7(o)** | **Your personal allotment** | Stops **forced sales** without consent |
| **14(h)** | **Sacred/historical sites** | **No sale EVER** — even with consent |

**14(h) > 7(i)** — **sacred sites win every time**.

---

### **Real Examples of 14(h) Wins**

| **Case** | **What Happened** | **Outcome** |
|--------|-------------------|-----------|
| **Gwichyaa Zyyo Cemetery (Fort Yukon)** | Old graveyard near Yukon River — Doyon wanted to log nearby. | **14(h) blocked it** — land withdrawn, corp paid fine. |
| **Danzhit Hanlai Trail** | Ancient Gwich’in trail used for travel/burials. | **14(h) nomination** → 200 acres protected. No Ambler Road access. |
| **Rampart Village Site** | Abandoned village — state tried to sell for mining. | **14(h) title to village corp** — mining stopped. |

