### **ICWA Relinquishment Effects — What It Means for You & Your Kids (Plain English)**

**ICWA = Indian Child Welfare Act (1978)**  
**Relinquishment** from tribal enrollment (like you did with TCC) **does NOT erase ICWA** for your children — **but it changes how it works**.  
Here’s the **real impact** on **your family**, **your land**, and **your fight**.

---

### **What ICWA Does (When You’re Enrolled)**
| **Protection** | **How It Works** |
|----------------|------------------|
| **Child Custody** | If your kid goes to foster care, **tribe gets first say** — not state. |
| **Adoption** | Non-Native families **can’t adopt** without tribal OK. |
| **Notice** | State **must tell tribe** about any case. |
| **Higher Proof** | State needs **strong evidence** to remove kids. |

**Goal**: Stop the **1960s–70s theft** of Native kids (1/3 taken from families).

---

### **What Happens When You Relinquish (Your Case)**

| **Effect** | **What It Means for You** |
|----------|---------------------------|
| **You Lose ICWA** | **You** are no longer “Indian child” or “parent” under ICWA. |  
| **Your Kids May KEEP ICWA** | If **they were enrolled** before you left — **they stay protected**. |  
| **Future Kids** | **No ICWA** unless you **re-enroll** or they join via other parent. |  
| **Grandkids** | **No ICWA** unless kids re-enroll. |  

**Key Rule (25 U.S.C. § 1903)**:  
> ICWA applies to **“Indian child”** = enrolled or **eligible + biological child of member**.

**You relinquished → You’re not a “member” → Future kids **not eligible** unless other parent is enrolled.**

---

### **ICWA Relinquishment Table — Your Family**

| **Person** | **ICWA Status After Your Relinquishment** |
|-----------|-------------------------------------------|
| **You** | **NO ICWA** — state treats you like non-Native in custody cases. |
| **Kids Born Before Relinquishment** | **YES ICWA** — if enrolled at birth. Tribe still has rights. |
| **Kids Born After** | **NO ICWA** — unless other parent is enrolled. |
| **Grandkids** | **NO ICWA** — unless kids re-enroll. |

---

### **How This Affects Your ANCSA Fight**

| **ICWA Effect** | **Impact on Land/Shares** |
|---------------|---------------------------|
| **No ICWA for You** | **Good** — state can’t use “ward of the tribe” to control your land. |
| **Kids Have ICWA** | **Good** — tribe **must protect their inheritance** (shares, allotments). |
| **Future Kids No ICWA** | **Risk** — state could try to say “no tribal tie” to block heirship. |

**BUT ANCSA IS STRONGER**:  
- **§7(c)**: Shares go to **lineal descendants** — **ICWA not required**.  
- **§7(o)**: Your land is **yours** — ICWA doesn’t touch it.  
- **§14(h)**: Sacred sites — **forever Native**, ICWA or not.

